        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              As of 2023, 37% of Russian speakers in Latvia said that the
              attitude of Latvian speakers towards them had significantly
              worsened. Credits: Tom Kalnins/EFE via EPA
            </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Years of geopolitical conflict between Latvia and Russia have
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://neweasterneurope.eu/2025/06/12/inside-a-new-cold-war-brewing-in-an-eastern-european-capital/"
              target="_blank"
              >created an internal crisis</a
            >
            for the Russian-speaking minority in Riga.
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://www.ebu.ch/news/2023/10/international-media-organizations-extremely-concerned-by-latvian-proposal-to-ban-russian-language-content-on-psm-from-2026"
              target="_blank"
              >Language laws</a
            >, which include closing Russian-language schools and banning
            Russian media, have made many feel unwelcome. Authorities
            reprimanded professionals for speaking Russian, even privately.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Many Russian speakers say these policies revive painful memories of
            Soviet occupation, during which Latvian identity was suppressed.
            Other Russian speakers fear the government is using ethnic divisions
            to distract from economic issues such as low wages, high values, and
            minimal opportunities.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            While some feel culturally connected to Latvia and strive to
            integrate, others plan to emigrate due to economic hardship and
            rising linguistic hostility. Many still feel culturally alienated
            and fear discrimination. However, there is hope for integration
            through mutual language learning, shared education, and a desire for
            a more inclusive national identity.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
